sentences: Shelby E. Starner (January 3, 1984 – June 22, 2003) was an American singer-songwriter and musician.
She signed a record deal with Warner Bros. Records in 1997, releasing her official debut single, "Don't Let Them" two years later.
She signed a record deal with Warner Bros. Records in 1997, releasing her official debut single, "Don't Let Them" two years later.
Starner released her debut studio album, From in the Shadows, later in 1999, but it was not commercially successful.
In 2000, Starner worked on a second album; it was never released.
In June 2003, Starner died suddenly at her home due to complications from bulimia nervosa.
Shelby E. Starner was born January 3, 1984, in East Stroudsburg, Pennsylvania, to Katherine Hass and Ray J. Starner.
At 12 years of age, Starner wrote the first song she deemed "acceptable" called "Straight A Student."
Later, in December 1996, Starner's father gifted her a three-hour slot at a studio where she recorded four demos of original songs.
In December 1997, Starner signed her a record deal with Warner Bros.
She enrolled in a home school program for her freshman year of high school.
1999: From in the Shadows ===
She released her debut album From in the Shadows, in 1999, through Warner Bros. Records.
She received coverage in Billboard, Newsweek, and USA Today and appeared on Entertainment Tonight.
